'''Emslie Horniman's Pleasance''' is a park in the [[London Borough of Kensington and Chelsea|Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] in [[London]]. Named after the London City Councillor [[Emslie John Horniman|Emslie J. Horniman]] who created it, and opened in 1914<ref name="LPGT">{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardenstrust.org/features/voysey2006.htm|title=The Voysey Garden|publisher=London Parks & Gardens Trust|author=Jemima Taylor|date=2006|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref>, it is the traditional kicking-off point of the [[Notting Hill Carnival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbkc.gov.uk/leisureandlibraries/parksandgardens/yourlocalpark/emsliehornimanspleasance.aspx|title=Emslie Horniman's Pleasance|publisher=The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref><ref name="unlike.net">{{cite web|url=http://london.unlike.net/locations/302607-Emslie-Horniman-s-Pleasance|publisher=unlike.net|title=Emslie Horniman's Pleasance: Enchanted gardens|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref>

The Pleasance contains a notable walled garden in the [[Arts and Crafts Movement|Arts and Crafts]] style, designed for Horniman by [[C. F. A. Voysey]].<ref name="LPGT"/><ref name="unlike.net"/> The garden is a [[Grade II listed]] structure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=KAC067|title=Emslie Horniman Pleasance Gardens, Kensington & Chelsea|publisher=London Parks & Gardens Trust|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref>

It is located on Bosworth Road in [[Ladbroke Grove]], on the southern side of the [[Grand Union Canal]], near to [[Notting Hill]]. The nearest tube station is [[Westbourne Park tube station|Westbourne Park]].

The park also contains tennis courts, five-a-side football pitches, a hard play area and a children's playground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbkc.gov.uk/az/az.asp?searchletter=&orgid=572|title=Emslie Horniman Pleasance Gardens|publisher=The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref>

